Czech discovery: a substance that also acts in ‘stealed’ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new connections to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works with viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the connection to common virus variants does not work as strongly as one of the already existing medicines.
The disease AIDS cannot be cured yet.
However, patients can extend their drug composition and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of the virus propagation also results in the development of the so-called resistant viruses, which are no longer effective.
The work of the experts of three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, of the VSCHT (Chemical-Technology University) Prague and of the University of Heidelberg opens the way for dealing with virus resistance.
They have demonstrated that the substances known as metalocarborans act on the protein that is responsible for the reproduction of HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the virus reproduction in a different way from all the medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come to new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding on the viral protein.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-faceted cages, consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms, coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Sustained and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV virus fragmentation caused by HIV protease, no mature viral particles would develop.
When we disable HIV protease, we also disable the proliferation of the virus in the patient's body, explains the scientists in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the Scientific Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this range of substances against HIV proteases is tested in the test tube, also against their resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metalocarboranes on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as in the clinically used medicinal products, but it does not lose its effect on the resistance variants that the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as its further features, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and possibility of further chemical designs, makes the Metalocarborans interesting for further development of effective anti-HIV drugs, says Pavlina Rezacova, Head of the Laboratory for Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
