Population Issues Division, while the number of people aged 60 and older in 2020 is expected to increase from 16.7 percent of the population by 2050 to 31.1% in an explosion-like way. This is well above the global average of around 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older people made up almost 22 percent of the reported inhabitants of Shanghai, while birth rates were below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City and Family Planning Commission, said that couples must have babies in the childbearing age to "help reduce the ratio of the ageing population and reduce the labour shortage of the future".
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the industrialized countries, such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
In the country's Constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial decision introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy must expect enormous fines - up to their threefold annual salary in some regions - and with discrimination at their workplace.
Chinese state representatives have attributed this policy to avoiding the critical demand of natural land resources, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of policies.
In rural regions, some officials who already had a child have forced pregnant women to leave.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude towards a single-child policy.
In 2004 they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007 the tone of many hard slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said that government representatives recently discussed even more radical changes, for example, allowing couples to have two children in which a partner is a single child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city in July to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters that taught families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines describing in detail who would be in demand for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city administration has sent out city staff and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and move information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice for those who had more than one child.
The reaction was not exactly encouraging, said family planning representatives.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a small rural town in the outer areas of Shanghai said that there was a recovery in the applications of couples who wanted a second child after the campaign was launched, the urban districts did not report any change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, still receives only four to five applications per month as an example.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the expected number of births in the city for 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than 2009, but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Family Planning Committee of the village of Caolu in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have children anymore.
They want to give their first the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this was also legal.
But they have, like many Chinese, only a minor health and life insurance of the government.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West falsely rate the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a structural engineer whose wife is pregnant in the seventh month with her first child.
Yes, we are deprived of the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples indicate psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the head of staff, said she only wanted to be a child because she was also an individual child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We're not used to taking care of others and don't really want to."
Chen Zieian, a 42-year-old who belongs to a translation company, said it inextricably.
For parents from the middle class with double careers through which the birth rate falls, he said, it is about being successful and for that one must be selfish.
The age group of today's 20-39-year-olds grew up to see their parents fight during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they don't want such a life for themselves, he said.
A single child, he said, also places enormous demands on the time of parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there is the space question -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and the life planning -- "If the child is 9 months old, you must already have a CV for the best preschools."
