Turkish Constitutional Court resolves pro-Kurdian party. Decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court announced on Friday the dissolution of the country's pro-Kurdish main party, a decision following immediately angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and Istanbul.
This decision threatens to make it very difficult for the government to do its job, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community in order to put an end to the conflicts which have been going on for 25 years.
The "Party for a Democratic Society" (DTP) has been dissolved because it has become a "rate for activities which are detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity", said the President of the Constitutional Court Hasim Kiliç four days after the decision to the press.
According to Kiliç, the decision would have been taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes needed to cast the resolution. Furthermore, he pointed out that 37 of the party’s leaders, including chairman Ahmet Türk and Parliamentary Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from the political situation for the duration of five years.
The judge also announced the abolition of parliamentary immunity, which Turkey and Tugluk enjoy, as well as the confiscation of the goods of the party.
The DTP now has 21 seats in Parliament (of 550).
The party leaders stated before the ruling that the parliamentarians would rather leave Parliament than meet as non-party parliamentarians.
The decision followed a procedure initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Turkish Federal Court of Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya. He accused the DTP of following the "wissenungen" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which is regarded by Ankara and many other countries as a terrorist organisation.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political display window of the PKK rebels.
The party guarantees that it has no connection to the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organisation and calls on the government to negotiate.
The Constitutional Court’s ruling is in the hands of the government, which is seeking to meet the Kurdish community and propose a series of measures to strengthen the Kurd’s rights in order to keep the Kurds from supporting the PKK and put an end to the conflicts.
The DTP leaders confirm that a resolution could lead to a re-ejection of tensions in south-east Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan's arrest conditions in recent weeks have led to clashes with the police.
Since the court's announcement, thousands of demonstrators have gathered in front of the DTP premises in the million-dollar city of Diyarbakir in the southeast, largely populated by Kurds.
Ordinary forces used tear gas grenades and water-throwers when the demonstrators began to throw Molotov cocktails and stones.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
According to the ruling, Turkey assumed that the decision of the court "will deepen the despair even further".
"Turkish cannot clarify this (Kurdish, n. d. Redaktion) question on the basis of the ban of a party," he explained to the press.
The government, consisting of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
"We oppose the closing of the parties on principle.
