The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-metre long and 1.50-metre-sized animal ran on two strong hind legs, had a long skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Science magazine of Thursday.
The animal lived some 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was then on the equator in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other palaeontologists began a excavation on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation, they gathered the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino early history
The name "Tawa" is derived from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the trias are extremely rare, most often only individual fragments can be found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
After the current teaching opinion, dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these Ur-Dinos is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the exes split into their three main development lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plants eating Ornithischia (foil basinsaur), for example, of the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original Theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of airbags, as they also possess the descendants of the Theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the airbags, breathing the birds is more efficient than the mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive Theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the relative line of the huge Sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestors of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the exes appeared there for the first time.
Thus, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America over all the continents, which at that time still formed a single land mass as a supercontinent Pangea.
For this, the fact that the team together with Tawa hallae found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot derive from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner from the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonn palaeontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could be distorted because in South America many primitive Dino fossils have simply been preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant land vertebrates of the Middle Ages, it is still mysterious.
During the Trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flight-sauriers, and with numerous other lizards.
Toward the end of the trias, dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relationship on the border of the Trias to the Jura died out.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass death that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact of a group of animals helped to flourish, which had also developed in the trias and since then had a shadow existence: the mammals.
