Hallucinations belong to the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also to amazingly many other diseases.
These include, in addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's and skull trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions even the brain of healthy people is hallucinating.
Hallucinations, says box, are composed of memory contents that are normally held back.
They arise when brain areas where sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; if our brain is running hot or if stimulation is missing.
Drugs can cause this condition as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But it's also stimuli, stress, pangs of love or other mental exceptions.
In recent studies, up to a third of the respondents reported having experienced hallucination at least once in life.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, where she attends the gymnasium.
A normal girl, actually.
If there were not the pictures and voices.
During the break it may happen that a sluggish boy with long, dark hair addresses it.
When it answers, the fellow students look surprised - nobody else sees or hears this boy.
They think this shy girl is a crazy daydream, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows.
