Border state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our too much awareness-centered world, imaginary experience is mostly pathologised, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Clinic for Psychiatry and Psychotherapy of the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a severe, painful disease, but it also has positive, creative - wahn is also a work of art from despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a particular form of traumatized alert consciousness.
Oneiroide are highly complex, detailed Quasi dreams, which the living person considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish from the watchful state even after.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis when fully conscious.
When a person is threatened by self- and world loss, for example by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of border state between dream and hallucination.
Since dealing with a situation in reality is not possible, a world change takes place, but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
An intense form of sense-making and sense-making in an in itself unbearable situation that allows people to have their own design ability, not to suffer in nothing of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Clausen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Heart Change" as the rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve surgery with subsequent heart transplant, while his body is condemned to motionlessness at the intensive care unit.
Clausen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, aboard a train's anatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who produce intoxicants from blood.
Swallowed by a Greek on the motorcycle in his home country, he surfes with his hospital bed in the early snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He goes up completely in the imaginary event, everything is real, even later in memory.
These inner journeys are fundamentally different from every dream for Claussen.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
By contrast, the memories of mental travel are super clear to me after years and in minor details.
More clearly and intensively even than truly experienced.
The intensity of this experience is spreading the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations, and drug noise show how fragile our inner images of external reality are also on guard.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist box, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that may well be enriching.
