75 % of the working mothers have been having problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination in work has increased in recent years, especially among the younger women who want to have children.
CSIC's study on women's fertility and career in Spain, in cooperation with the Institute for Women, comes to this conclusion.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt as to whether 75% of women working in employment see their career opportunities restricted on the labour market due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to create a family and the number of children, depending on whether women work or not and, if so, what kind of occupation they practice.
Those of them who do no other activity outside the house, work only half a day or do not have a fixed employment contract will rather be mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women move with a permanent employment, especially in the public sector, the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"The women in the age group between 35 and 49 years of age with a fixed position receive their first child on average only 3.7 years after moving together, a number that increases to 4.1 years for women with permanent employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have been moving together and the first child has only realized much later.
Furthermore, the type of work also has a major influence on maternity, though less than the calendar in terms of conception," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that needs to be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child, the higher the level of education.
This difference could also be seen in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group were between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they had only the primary education or a higher education, on average with 25.1 or 32.1 for the first time.
There is also a further difference between women depending on their level of education.
While the women with the primary degree are already married before their first permanent position and have their first child, women with a middle or high school degree are doing exactly different and are looking for a permanent position and getting married after it and then getting their first child, says Delgado.
