Support for brake maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock brake system at that time, and just as with the stability control ESP, the emergency braking aid systems must become a requirement in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and light transporters, and for the remaining vehicles, a karenz period has been set by the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of foot-and-mouths, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake maneuver, which recognizes the system on the brake pedal by means of the brake strength performed by the driver.
However, this system does not exercise this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to hit the brake pedal before the crash and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes in the braking system with maximum force and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the brake distance that a car saves during the braking process.
According to a study conducted by the EU, up to 1,100 fatal accidents that cause harm every year could be prevented if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is expected that every fourth accident with personal injury could be prevented - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if it becomes necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is inevitable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
