Every day thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are dragged into the workshops where an expert has to assess the damage caused and the costs of repair.
No accident is the same and the calculation of the costs for the parts and hours of work can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including the parts and working hours, may take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer science tools, it is a matter of minutes
Therefore, almost 100 % of the experts use this type of system.
Service providers and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from manufacturers to process them afterwards and offer them to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all opinions are produced with their products.
GtMotive and Eurotax are the two other companies competing in the tool market for assessment and preparation of a report.
Working with the data that manufacturers provide is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Sales Manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are cooperated, each providing the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is getting larger and bigger, until the point that more versions, variants and motorizations have been on the market over the past five years than they have been in the past fifteen years.
As soon as a new car enters the market, work begins for the companies.
It is a laborious task, because each one of the thousand parts of the vehicle has to be catagolated and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image, on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds quickly.
In the case of less common cars, it may take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information at 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, they have information about Porsche models, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the road-driven vehicle park, it is above 99%.
For the purpose of carrying out documentation work and the production of databases, Audatex has eight centres distributed worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them specialises in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics for mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests EUR 90 million annually in the development of these databases.
Every month they record 2.5 million data and their customers get the updates every second day.
The development of this huge flow of information enables companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use of repairs and repairs, but, depending on the country, there are also tools for the management of scrap parts or for the calculation of the fall or residual value of a car.
